<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1939-09-28T13:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1939-09-28T13:00:00-05:00" n="857" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d857">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">300.115(39) Benecke, Alexander/6:
                            Telegram</note>
                        <head>
                            <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in the United Kingdom</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Kennedy</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss>
                            </hi>
                        </head>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">London</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1939-09-28T19:00:00+01:00">September
                                    28, 1939—7 p.m.</date>
                                <lb/> [Received September 28—2:16 p.m.]</dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>1858. Your 1083, September 27, 11 a.m. Ministry of Economic Warfare
                            stated that the British Government is taking no action whatever <pb facs="0807" n="795" xml:id="pg_795"/> at present against exports
                            direct or indirect from Germany to neutral countries carried on neutral
                            ships, the only exception being arms and munitions which there might be
                            reason to believe it was intended to transfer to a German raider.</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">Kennedy</hi>
                            </signed>
                        </closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>